04433nam a22005535i 9780520935655DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209356557 a10.1525/97805209356552doi  a(DE-B1597)520484  a(OCoLC)51825753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML3528.8b.K54 2002 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a781.62/924a781.6292407300aAmerican Klezmer :bIts Roots and Offshoots /cMark Slobin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1. American Klezmer: A Brief History -- t2. Klezmer-loshn: The Language of Jewish Folk Musicians -- t3. Di Rusishe Progresiv Muzikal Yunyon No. 1 fun Amerike: The First Klezmer Union in America -- t4. The Klezmer in Jewish Philadelphia, 1915-70 -- t5. "All My Life a Musician": Ben Bazyler, a European Klezmer in America -- t6. Bulgǎreascǎ /Bulgarish /Bulgar: The Transformation of a Klezmer Dance Genre -- t7. Sounds of Sensibility -- t8. KlezKamp and the Rise of Yiddish Cultural Literacy -- t9. Newish, Not Jewish: A Tale of Two Bands -- t10. An Insider's View: How We Traveled from Obscurity to the Klezmer Establishment in Twenty Years -- t11. Why We Do This Anyway: Klezmer as Jewish Youth Subculture -- tSources -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKlezmer, the Yiddish word for a folk instrumental musician, has come to mean a person, a style, and a scene. This musical subculture came to the United States with the late-nineteenth-century Jewish immigrants from Eastern Europe. Although it had declined in popularity by the middle of the twentieth century, this lively music is now enjoying recognition among music fans of all stripes. Today, klezmer flourishes in the United States and abroad in the world music and accompany Jewish celebrations. The outstanding essays collected in this volume investigate American klezmer: its roots, its evolution, and its spirited revitalization. The contributors to American Klezmer include every kind of authority on the subject--from academics to leading musicians--and they offer a wide range of perspectives on the musical, social, and cultural history of klezmer in American life. The first half of this volume concentrates on the early history of klezmer, using folkloric sources, records of early musicians unions, and interviews with the last of the immigrant musicians. The second part of the collection examines the klezmer "revival" that began in the 1970s. Several of these essays were written by the leaders of this movement, or draw on interviews with them, and give firsthand accounts of how klezmer is transmitted and how its practitioners maintain a balance between preservation and innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aJewsvMusicvCongresses. 0aJewsxMusicxCongresses. 0aKlezmer musicvCongresses. 0aKlezmer musicxCongresses. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aSlobin, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520935655.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles